Tim,<br>
     I believe the answer to your question varies with the very different experiences and circumstances of each veteran.  I won't speak for the guys who were regularly out on operations and saw a lot of action, but those of us who spent most of our time in the rear were often kept busy enough with perimeter duty, court martial cases and a hundred and one other things.  When we had extra time, it wasn't often spent in philosophical discussions, but rather in things like poker games.  A sizeable number of guys also spent a good deal of time seeking female companionship.<br>
     While I didn't get a lot of information beyond the local picture during my tour; I didn't need to ask questions later about what was going wrong.  It didn't take a rocket scientist to figure out that we were spinning our wheels.  The best explanation I've seen of why American troops referred to back home in the USA as &quot;The World&quot;; was that the place and situation we were in was too abnormal to actually be real.  The questions are more of the nature of why didn't the guys in charge in DC either get it right or stay out altogether, or what have we gained or lost as a nation at the cost of the lives ended in the war and the national trauma the country is still recovering from, or more personally why am I alive and _________ is gone, or how does one live with the ghosts of the past that won't go away.  And those are not all the questions.  As for me, the second one I mentioned concerns me the most.  If you read through the posts on site thoroughly; you'll find others have both similar and different questions and priorities.
